'''Cipriano Targioni''' (1672&ndash;1748) was an [[Italy|Italian]] scientific instrument maker.

Born in [[Florence]], Targioni studied [[medicine]] at the [[University of Pisa]]. On returning to his native town, he was named supervisor of the observations and physical experiments carried out in the [[Galleria Medicea]] by order of the [[Grand Duke of Tuscany]], [[Cosimo III de' Medici]]. He developed methods for preserving animal corpses for anatomical dissection. Targioni also conducted meteorological observations on a systematic basis beginning in 1728.<ref>Dechambre, Amédée. [https://books.google.com/books?id=bP4IaAsUjGQC&dq=Cipriano%20Targioni%201728&pg=PA757#v=onepage&q=Cipriano%20Targioni%201728&f=false Dictionnaire encyclopédique des sciences médicales.] Asselin, 1885. p756-757</ref>

