'''Putrefying bacteria''' are [[bacteria]] involved in [[putrefaction]] of living matter. Along with other [[decomposer]]s, they play a critical role in [[nitrogen cycle|recycling nitrogen]] from dead organisms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pmgbiology.com/tag/nitrogen-cycle/ |accessdate=10 July 2016 |title=4.10 Bacteria of the Nitrogen Cycle: A understanding for GCSE Biology |publisher=PMG Biology |date=12 April 2014}}</ref>
==Nitrogen cycle== Putrefying bacteria use [[amino acid]]s or [[urea]] as an energy source to decompose dead organisms. In the process, they produce [[ammonium]] ions. [[Nitrifying bacteria]] then convert this ammonium into [[nitrate]], which can then be used by plants to create more proteins thus completing the nitrogen cycle.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VCi6chr5Ht0C&pg=PA158&dq=putrefying+bacteria#v=onepage&q=putrefying%20bacteria&f=false|title=Biology|isbn=9780435580001|author1=Fosbery|first1=Richard|last2=McLean|first2=Jean|year=1996}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Decomposition]] *[[Anaerobic organism]]
