{{Infobox software | title = spaCy | name = spaCy | logo = SpaCy logo.svg | author = Matthew Honnibal | developer = [https://explosion.ai Explosion AI], [https://github.com/explosion/spaCy/graphs/contributors various] | released = February 2015<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing spaCy |publisher=explosion.ai |url=https://explosion.ai/blog/introducing-spacy|accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref> | latest release version = 2.0 | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2017|11|07|df=yes}} | repo = {{URL|https://github.com/explosion/spaCy}} | status = active | programming language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]], [[Cython]] | operating system = Linux, Windows, macOS, OS X | platform = cross-platform | genre = [[Natural language processing]] | license = [[MIT License|MIT]] | website = {{URL|https://spacy.io}} }}
'''spaCy''' ({{IPAc-en|s|p|eɪ|ˈ|s|iː}} {{respell|spay|SEE|'}}) is an [[Open-source software|open-source]] software library for advanced [[Natural language processing|Natural Language Processing]], written in the programming languages [[Python (programming language)|Python]] and [[Cython]].<ref>Choi et al. (2015). [https://aclweb.org/anthology/P/P15/P15-1038.pdf It Depends: Dependency Parser Comparison Using A Web-based Evaluation Tool].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/18/googles-new-artificial-intelligence-cant-understand-these-sentences-can-you/|title=Google’s new artificial intelligence can’t understand these sentences. Can you?|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-12-18}}</ref> The library is published under the [[MIT License|MIT license]] and currently offers statistical [[Artificial neural network|neural network]] models for English, German, Spanish, Portuguese, French, Italian, Dutch and multi-language [[Named-entity recognition|NER]], as well as [[Tokenizer|tokenization]] for various other languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacy.io/usage/models#languages|title=Models & Languages {{!}} spaCy Usage Documentation|last=|first=|date=|website=spacy.io|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref>
Unlike [[Natural Language Toolkit|NLTK]], which is widely used for teaching and research, spaCy focuses on providing software for production usage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacy.io/usage/facts-figures#other-libraries|title=Facts & Figures - spaCy|website=spacy.io|language=en|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref><ref name="Bird-Klein-Loper-Baldridge">{{cite journal|last=Bird|first=Steven|author2=Klein, Ewan|author3=Loper, Edward|author4=Baldridge, Jason|date=|year=2008|title=Multidisciplinary instruction with the Natural Language Toolkit|url=https://www.aclweb.org/anthology/W/W08/W08-0208.pdf|journal=Proceedings of the Third Workshop on Issues in Teaching Computational Linguistics, ACL|version=|publisher=|volume=|page=|pages=|accessdate=|via=}}</ref> As of version 1.0, spaCy also supports [[deep learning]] workflows<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/explosion/spaCy/releases/tag/v1.0.0|title=explosion/spaCy|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-12-18}}</ref> that allow connecting statistical models trained by popular [[machine learning]] libraries like [[TensorFlow]], [[Keras]], [[Scikit-learn]] or [[PyTorch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacy.io/usage/facts-figures#other-libraries|title=Facts & Figures {{!}} spaCy Usage Documentation|last=|first=|date=|website=spacy.io|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref> spaCy's [[machine learning]] library, Thinc, is also available as a separate [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Python (programming language)|Python]] library.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/explosion/thinc|title=explosion/thinc|website=GitHub|access-date=2016-12-30}}</ref> On November 7, 2017, version 2.0 was released.<ref>{{Citation|title=spaCy: 💫 Industrial-strength Natural Language Processing (NLP) with Python and Cython|date=2017-11-08|url=https://github.com/explosion/spaCy|publisher=Explosion AI|accessdate=2017-11-08}}</ref> It features [[convolutional neural network]] models for [[part-of-speech tagging]], dependency parsing and [[Named-entity recognition|named entity recognition]], as well as API improvements around training and updating models, and constructing custom processing pipelines.
== Main features == * Non-destructive [[Tokenization (lexical analysis)|tokenization]] * [[Named-entity recognition|Named entity recognition]] * "Alpha tokenization" support for over 25 languages<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacy.io/usage/models|title=Models & Languages - spaCy|website=spacy.io|language=en|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref> * [[Statistical model|Statistical models]] models for 8 languages<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacy.io/usage/models|title=Models & Languages {{!}} spaCy Usage Documentation|last=|first=|date=|website=spacy.io|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref> * Pre-trained [[Word embedding|word vectors]] * [[Part-of-speech tagging]] * Labelled [[Dependency grammar|dependency]] parsing * Syntax-driven [[Sentence boundary disambiguation|sentence segmentation]] * [[Document classification|Text classification]] * Built-in visualizers for [[syntax]] and [[Named-entity recognition|named entities]] * [[Deep learning]] integration
== Extensions and visualizers == [[File:Displacy.png|alt=Dependency parse tree visualization generated with the displaCy visualizer|thumb|500x500px|Dependency [[parse tree]] visualization generated with the [https://demos.explosion.ai/displacy/ displaCy visualizer] ]] spaCy comes with several extensions and visualizations that are available as free, [[Open-source software|open-source]] libraries: * [https://github.com/explosion/thinc Thinc]: A [[machine learning]] library optimized for [[Central processing unit|CPU]] usage and [[deep learning]] with text input. * [https://github.com/explosion/sense2vec sense2vec]: A library for computing word similarities, based on [[Word2vec]] and sense2vec.<ref>Trask et al. (2015). [https://arxiv.org/abs/1511.06388 sense2vec - A Fast and Accurate Method for Word Sense Disambiguation In Neural Word Embeddings].</ref> * [https://github.com/explosion/displacy displaCy]: An [[Open-source software|open-source]] dependency [[parse tree]] visualizer built with [[JavaScript]], [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]] and [[Scalable Vector Graphics|SVG]]. * [https://github.com/explosion/displacy-ent displaCy<sup>ENT</sup>]: An [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Named-entity recognition|named entity]] visualizer built with [[JavaScript]] and [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]].
