{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}

'''Taisia Maximova Stadnichenko''' (9 October 1894 – 26 November 1958) was a Russian born geologist and chemist whose fieldwork was focused on the distribution of [[germanium]] and the minor-element content in [[coal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rruff.info/doclib/cm/vol6/CM6_412.pdf|title=BIOLOGICAL SKETCHES OF DECEASED MEMBERS|last=Breger|first=Irving|date=|website=RRUFF Data|publisher=|access-date=31 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104010829/http://rruff.info/doclib/cm/vol6/CM6_412.pdf|archivedate=4 November 2016}}</ref> She was born in Taganash, Crimea on October 9, 1894 and died on November 26,1958 at the age of sixty-four due to a heart ailment.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=rUCUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT520&lpg=PT520&dq=Tasia+Stadnichenko&source=bl&ots=7eM_E8Gfn5&sig=GlMObVF-TawDnFjLUiW0FKE3hXs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMypuHsOnWAhXGxrwKHeAjA8EQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=Tasia%20Stadnichenko&f=false|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: Pioneering Lives From Ancient Times to the Mid-20th Century|last=Ogilvie|first=Marilyn|last2=Harvey|first2=Joy|date=2003-12-16|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135963439|language=en}}</ref>  She attended [[Saint Petersburg State University|Petrograd University]] and joined the Russian Geological Survey before moving to the United States in 1918 to act as an interpreter for the Russian mission throughout [[World War I]]. After the war she continued her professional life as a researcher at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign|University of Illinois]] and as a professor at [[Vassar College]] from 1922 to 1935.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=rUCUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT520&lpg=PT520&dq=Tasia+Stadnichenko+geologist&source=bl&ots=7dT-y4Eak3&sig=4M5m6zNag9yKTDW7pFqDDLkVhRI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbz5qC1YrQAhWLwlQKHcA4DcsQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Tasia%20Stadnichenko%20geologist&f=false|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: Pioneering Lives From Ancient Times to the Mid-20th Century|last=Ogilvie|first=Marilyn|last2=Harvey|first2=Joy|date=2003-12-16|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135963439|language=en}}</ref> In 1935, Stadnichenko led the first [[United States Geological Survey|U.S Geological Survey]] exploring the minor-element distribution within coal by collecting samples of coal ash for element content analysis, which found germanium and other elements within the coal ash.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=DrUPAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&hl=en&pg=GBS.SL1-PA3|title=Geochemistry of Minor Elements in Coals of the Northern Great Plains Coal Province|last=Zubovic|first=Peter|last2=Stadnichenko|first2=Taisia|last3=Sheffey|first3=Nola B.|date=1961-01-01|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|language=en}}</ref> Stadnichenko is widely considered instrumental in the discovery and understanding of coal's structure and origin.<ref name=":0" />

