[[File:WTEC logo.png|thumb|Logo]]
The '''Women's Technology Empowerment Centre''', often referred to as '''W.TEC''', is a non-profit organization that focuses on empowering Nigerian women and girls through the use of technology.<ref name="CPAFRICA">{{cite web|last1=Segun-Amao|first1=Bimbola|title=CPAfrica interviews Oreoluwa Somolu Lesi of Women's Technology Empowerment Centre|url=http://www.cp-africa.com/2015/07/31/cpafrica-interviews-oreoluwa-somolu-lesi-of-womens-technology-empowerment-centre/|website=CPAFRICA|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> It was founded in 2008 by [[Oreoluwa Lesi]] after noticing a gender gap in understanding of [[Information and Communications Technology]] (ICT) throughout Nigeria and other African countries.<ref name="empowering">{{cite web|last1=Homawoo|first1=Jemima|title=EMPOWERING WOMEN IN STEM SERIES: Nigeria’s Women’s Technology Empowerment Centre|url=http://www.instepp.org/empowering-women-in-stem-series-nigerias-womens-technology-empowerment-centre/|website=InStepp Incorporated|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> Services and programs offered by W.TEC include mentoring, training in technology, technology camp, awareness campaigns, collaborative projects, and research and publication.<ref name="empowering" /><ref name="TechTrends">{{cite web|last1=Omeruo|first1=Kenneth|title=Women’s Technology Empowerment Centre (W.TEC) Nigeria Announces its 8th Girls Technology Camp for August 2015|url=http://www.techtrendsng.com/womens-technology-empowerment-centre-w-tec-nigeria-announces-its-8th-girls-technology-camp-for-august-2015/|website=TechTrendsng.com|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Facebook partnered with W.TEC to take efforts toward improved Internet safety.<ref name="Business">{{cite web|title=Facebook rallies partners to unite for a safer, better Internet|url=https://www.businessghana.com/site/news/technology/141294/Facebook-rallies-partners-to-unite-for-a-safer-better-Internet|website=BusinessGhana|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>

